# Integrating the Final Backend Endpoints

You are exactly right! We have a powerful backend with lots of features, but our frontend only uses `/auth/login`, `/auth/register`, and `GET /queues`. 

Here is the plan to build the final UI pages to consume the rest of your backend endpoints:

## 1. The Customer View: Joining & Tracking
#### [NEW] `app/queue/[id]/page.tsx`
When a customer clicks "Join Queue" from the Home page, they go here.
- **Endpoints Used:**
  - `GET /queues/{id}` (to load the queue details)
  - `POST /queues/{id}/join` (to actually join and get a token)
  - `POST /queues/{id}/leave` (if they cancel)
- **Real-Time Magic:** This page will connect to our **WebSocket** (`/queues/{id}/ws`) to listen for live token updates so the customer can watch the line move without refreshing the page!

## 2. The Operator View: Calling the Next Patient
#### [NEW] `app/operator/[id]/page.tsx`
When an Admin or Operator clicks "Manage Queue" on the Home page, they go here.
- **Endpoints Used:**
  - `GET /queues/{id}` (to see the queue details)
  - `POST /queues/{id}/advance` (The big "Call Next Patient" button)
- **What it does:** When they click the button, it updates the database and broadcasts the new number to all the customers' phones via the WebSocket.

## 3. The Admin View: Editing & Deleting
We will add small edit/delete buttons to the QueueList for admins.
- **Endpoints Used:**
  - `PATCH /queues/{id}` (Edit capacity or name)
  - `DELETE /queues/{id}` (Remove the queue completely)

